# Events

## Purpose
Defines the platform-to-ECS event pipeline. Platform events (`pg::Event` subclasses) are
created by the window layer from OS messages and handed synchronously to `Application::OnEvent`.
The application immediately translates them into ECS event component entities via
`World::EmplaceExternalEvent`. ECS systems read only the component form — they never access
`pg::Event` objects directly.

## Platform Event → ECS Component Mapping

| Platform Event | ECS Component |
|---|---|
| `KeyPressedEvent` | `KeyPressedEventComponent` (`int m_KeyCode`) |
| `KeyReleasedEvent` | `KeyReleasedEventComponent` (`int m_KeyCode`) |
| `KeyTypedEvent` | `KeyTypedEventComponent` (`int m_KeyCode`) |
| `MouseMovedEvent` | `MouseMovedEventComponent` (`float m_MouseX, m_MouseY`) |
| `MouseScrolledEvent` | `MouseScrolledEventComponent` (`float m_XOffset, m_YOffset`) |
| `MouseButtonPressedEvent` | `MouseButtonPressedEventComponent` (`int m_Button`) |
| `MouseButtonReleasedEvent` | `MouseButtonReleasedEventComponent` (`int m_Button`) |
| `WindowResizeEvent` | `WindowResizeEventComponent` (`unsigned int m_Width, m_Height`) |
| `WindowCloseEvent` | `WindowCloseEventComponent` (marker, `bool m_Dummy`) |

Every event entity also receives `EventComponent` (trivial tag). `World::ClearEvents` destroys
all entities carrying `EventComponent` at the end of every frame — event entities are
single-frame only.

Key codes are translated through `PlatformInput::GetKeyCode` / `GetMouseButtonCode` before being
stored, so systems always see platform-independent `PG_KEY_*` / `PG_MOUSE_BUTTON_*` constants.

## File Location
`Code/PigeonLib/Pigeon/Events/` — platform event classes (`pg::Event` hierarchy)
`Code/PigeonLib/Pigeon/Core/` — ECS event component structs
